#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:5
msgid "NumPy 2.1.0 Release Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:7
msgid ""
"NumPy 2.1.0 provides support for the upcoming Python 3.13 release and drops "
"support for Python 3.9. In addition to the usual bug fixes and updated "
"Python support, it helps get us back into our usual release cycle after the "
"extended development of 2.0. The highlights for this release are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:12
msgid "Support for the array-api 2023.12 standard."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:13
msgid "Support for Python 3.13."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:14
msgid "Preliminary support for free threaded Python 3.13."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:16
msgid "Python versions 3.10-3.13 are supported in this release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:20
msgid "New functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:23
msgid "New function ``numpy.unstack``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:25
msgid ""
"A new function ``np.unstack(array, axis=...)`` was added, which splits an "
"array into a tuple of arrays along an axis. It serves as the inverse of "
"`numpy.stack`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:29
msgid "(`gh-26579 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26579>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:33
msgid "Deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:35
msgid ""
"The ``fix_imports`` keyword argument in ``numpy.save`` is deprecated. Since "
"NumPy 1.17, ``numpy.save`` uses a pickle protocol that no longer supports "
"Python 2, and ignored ``fix_imports`` keyword. This keyword is kept only for "
"backward compatibility. It is now deprecated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:40
msgid "(`gh-26452 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26452>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:42
msgid ""
"Passing non-integer inputs as the first argument of `bincount` is now "
"deprecated, because such inputs are silently cast to integers with no "
"warning about loss of precision."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:46
msgid "(`gh-27076 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/27076>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:50
msgid "Expired deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:52
msgid ""
"Scalars and 0D arrays are disallowed for ``numpy.nonzero`` and ``numpy."
"ndarray.nonzero``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:54
msgid "(`gh-26268 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26268>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:56
msgid ""
"``set_string_function`` internal function was removed and "
"``PyArray_SetStringFunction`` was stubbed out."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:59 ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:166
msgid "(`gh-26611 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26611>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:63
msgid "C API changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:66
msgid "API symbols now hidden but customizable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:67
msgid ""
"NumPy now defaults to hide the API symbols it adds to allow all NumPy API "
"usage.  This means that by default you cannot dynamically fetch the NumPy "
"API from another library (this was never possible on windows)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:71
msgid ""
"If you are experiencing linking errors related to ``PyArray_API`` or "
"``PyArray_RUNTIME_VERSION``, you can define the ``NPY_API_SYMBOL_ATTRIBUTE`` "
"to opt-out of this change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:75
msgid ""
"If you are experiencing problems due to an upstream header including NumPy, "
"the solution is to make sure you ``#include \"numpy/ndarrayobject.h\"`` "
"before their header and import NumPy yourself based on  ``including-the-c-"
"api``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:79
msgid "(`gh-26103 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26103>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:82
msgid "Many shims removed from npy_3kcompat.h"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:83
msgid ""
"Many of the old shims and helper functions were removed from ``npy_3kcompat."
"h``. If you find yourself in need of these, vendor the previous version of "
"the file into your codebase."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:87
msgid "(`gh-26842 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26842>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:90
msgid "New ``PyUFuncObject`` field ``process_core_dims_func``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:91
msgid ""
"The field ``process_core_dims_func`` was added to the structure "
"``PyUFuncObject``.  For generalized ufuncs, this field can be set to a "
"function of type ``PyUFunc_ProcessCoreDimsFunc`` that will be called when "
"the ufunc is called. It allows the ufunc author to check that core "
"dimensions satisfy additional constraints, and to set output core dimension "
"sizes if they have not been provided."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:98
msgid "(`gh-26908 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26908>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:102
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:105
msgid "Preliminary Support for Free-Threaded CPython 3.13"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:107
msgid ""
"CPython 3.13 will be available as an experimental free-threaded build. See "
"https://py-free-threading.github.io, `PEP 703 <https://peps.python.org/"
"pep-0703/>`_ and the `CPython 3.13 release notes <https://docs.python."
"org/3.13/whatsnew/3.13.html#free-threaded-cpython>`_ for more detail about "
"free-threaded Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:113
msgid ""
"NumPy 2.1 has preliminary support for the free-threaded build of CPython "
"3.13. This support was enabled by fixing a number of C thread-safety issues "
"in NumPy. Before NumPy 2.1, NumPy used a large number of C global static "
"variables to store runtime caches and other state. We have either refactored "
"to avoid the need for global state, converted the global state to thread-"
"local state, or added locking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:120
msgid ""
"Support for free-threaded Python does not mean that NumPy is thread safe. "
"Read-only shared access to ndarray should be safe. NumPy exposes shared "
"mutable state and we have not added any locking to the array object itself "
"to serialize access to shared state. Care must be taken in user code to "
"avoid races if you would like to mutate the same array in multiple threads. "
"It is certainly possible to crash NumPy by mutating an array simultaneously "
"in multiple threads, for example by calling a ufunc and the ``resize`` "
"method simultaneously. For now our guidance is: \"don't do that\". In the "
"future we would like to provide stronger guarantees."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:130
msgid ""
"Object arrays in particular need special care, since the GIL previously "
"provided locking for object array access and no longer does. See `Issue "
"#27199 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/27199>`_ for more information "
"about object arrays in the free-threaded build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:135
msgid ""
"If you are interested in free-threaded Python, for example because you have "
"a multiprocessing-based workflow that you are interested in running with "
"Python threads, we encourage testing and experimentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:139
msgid ""
"If you run into problems that you suspect are because of NumPy, please `open "
"an issue <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/new/choose>`_, checking "
"first if the bug also occurs in the \"regular\" non-free-threaded CPython "
"3.13 build. Many threading bugs can also occur in code that releases the "
"GIL; disabling the GIL only makes it easier to hit threading bugs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:145
msgid ""
"(`gh-26157 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/"
"issues/26157#issuecomment-2233864940>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:147
msgid ""
"``numpy.reshape`` and ``numpy.ndarray.reshape`` now support ``shape`` and "
"``copy`` arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:150
msgid "(`gh-26292 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26292>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:152
msgid ""
"NumPy now supports DLPack v1, support for older versions will be deprecated "
"in the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:155
msgid "(`gh-26501 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26501>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:157
msgid ""
"``numpy.asanyarray`` now supports ``copy`` and ``device`` arguments, "
"matching ``numpy.asarray``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:160
msgid "(`gh-26580 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26580>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:162
msgid ""
"``numpy.printoptions``, ``numpy.get_printoptions``, and ``numpy."
"set_printoptions`` now support a new option, ``override_repr``, for defining "
"custom ``repr(array)`` behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:168
msgid ""
"``numpy.cumulative_sum`` and ``numpy.cumulative_prod`` were added as Array "
"API compatible alternatives for ``numpy.cumsum`` and ``numpy.cumprod``. The "
"new functions can include a fixed initial (zeros for ``sum`` and ones for "
"``prod``) in the result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:173 ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:180
#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:184
msgid "(`gh-26724 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26724>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:175
msgid ""
"``numpy.clip`` now supports ``max`` and ``min`` keyword arguments which are "
"meant to replace ``a_min`` and ``a_max``. Also, for ``np.clip(a)`` or ``np."
"clip(a, None, None)`` a copy of the input array will be returned instead of "
"raising an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:182
msgid "``numpy.astype`` now supports ``device`` argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:187
msgid "``f2py`` can generate freethreading-compatible C extensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:188
msgid ""
"Pass ``--freethreading-compatible`` to the f2py CLI tool to produce a C "
"extension marked as compatible with the free threading CPython interpreter. "
"Doing so prevents the interpreter from re-enabling the GIL at runtime when "
"it imports the C extension. Note that ``f2py`` does not analyze fortran code "
"for thread safety, so you must verify that the wrapped fortran code is "
"thread safe before marking the extension as compatible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:195
msgid "(`gh-26981 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26981>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:199
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:202
msgid ""
"``histogram`` auto-binning now returns bin sizes >=1 for integer input data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:203
msgid ""
"For integer input data, bin sizes smaller than 1 result in spurious empty "
"bins.  This is now avoided when the number of bins is computed using one of "
"the algorithms provided by ``histogram_bin_edges``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:207
msgid "(`gh-12150 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/12150>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:210
msgid ""
"``ndarray`` shape-type parameter is now covariant and bound to "
"``tuple[int, ...]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:211
msgid ""
"Static typing for ``ndarray`` is a long-term effort that continues with this "
"change.  It is a generic type with type parameters for the shape and the "
"data type.  Previously, the shape type parameter could be any value.  This "
"change restricts it to a tuple of ints, as one would expect from using "
"``ndarray.shape``.  Further, the shape-type parameter has been changed from "
"invariant to covariant.  This change also applies to the subtypes of "
"``ndarray``, e.g. ``numpy.ma.MaskedArray``.  See the `typing docs <https://"
"typing.readthedocs.io/en/latest/reference/generics.html#variance-of-generic-"
"types>`_ for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:221
msgid "(`gh-26081 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26081>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:224
msgid ""
"``np.quantile`` with method ``closest_observation`` chooses nearest even "
"order statistic"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:225
msgid ""
"This changes the definition of nearest for border cases from the nearest odd "
"order statistic to nearest even order statistic. The numpy implementation "
"now matches other reference implementations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:229
msgid "(`gh-26656 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26656>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:232
msgid "``lapack_lite`` is now thread safe"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:233
msgid ""
"NumPy provides a minimal low-performance version of LAPACK named "
"``lapack_lite`` that can be used if no BLAS/LAPACK system is detected at "
"build time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:236
msgid ""
"Until now, ``lapack_lite`` was not thread safe. Single-threaded use cases "
"did not hit any issues, but running linear algebra operations in multiple "
"threads could lead to errors, incorrect results, or segfaults due to data "
"races."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:240
msgid ""
"We have added a global lock, serializing access to ``lapack_lite`` in "
"multiple threads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:243
msgid "(`gh-26750 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26750>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:246
msgid "The ``numpy.printoptions`` context manager is now thread and async-safe"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:247
msgid ""
"In prior versions of NumPy, the printoptions were defined using a "
"combination of Python and C global variables. We have refactored so the "
"state is stored in a python ``ContextVar``, making the context manager "
"thread and async-safe."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:251
msgid "(`gh-26846 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26846>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:254
msgid "Type hinting ``numpy.polynomial``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:255
msgid ""
"Starting from the 2.1 release, PEP 484 type annotations have been included "
"for the functions and convenience classes in ``numpy.polynomial`` and its "
"sub-packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:259
msgid "(`gh-26897 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26897>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:262
msgid "Improved ``numpy.dtypes`` type hints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:263
msgid ""
"The type annotations for ``numpy.dtypes`` are now a better reflection of the "
"runtime: The ``numpy.dtype`` type-aliases have been replaced with "
"specialized ``dtype`` *subtypes*, and the previously missing annotations for "
"``numpy.dtypes.StringDType`` have been added."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:268
msgid "(`gh-27008 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/27008>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:272
msgid "Performance improvements and changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:274
msgid ""
"``numpy.save`` now uses pickle protocol version 4 for saving arrays with "
"object dtype, which allows for pickle objects larger than 4GB and improves "
"saving speed by about 5% for large arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:278
msgid "(`gh-26388 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26388>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:280
msgid ""
"OpenBLAS on x86_64 and i686 is built with fewer kernels. Based on "
"benchmarking, there are 5 clusters of performance around these kernels: "
"``PRESCOTT NEHALEM SANDYBRIDGE HASWELL SKYLAKEX``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:284 ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:288
#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:293
msgid "(`gh-27147 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/27147>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:286
msgid "OpenBLAS on windows is linked without quadmath, simplifying licensing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:290
msgid ""
"Due to a regression in OpenBLAS on windows, the performance improvements "
"when using multiple threads for OpenBLAS 0.3.26 were reverted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:296
msgid "``ma.cov`` and ``ma.corrcoef`` are now significantly faster"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:297
msgid ""
"The private function has been refactored along with ``ma.cov`` and ``ma."
"corrcoef``. They are now significantly faster, particularly on large, masked "
"arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:301 ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:331
msgid "(`gh-26285 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26285>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:305
msgid "Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:307
msgid ""
"As ``numpy.vecdot`` is now a ufunc it has a less precise signature. This is "
"due to the limitations of ufunc's typing stub."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:310
msgid "(`gh-26313 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26313>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:312
msgid ""
"``numpy.floor``, ``numpy.ceil``, and ``numpy.trunc`` now won't perform "
"casting to a floating dtype for integer and boolean dtype input arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:315
msgid "(`gh-26766 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/26766>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:318
msgid "``ma.corrcoef`` may return a slightly different result"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:319
msgid ""
"A pairwise observation approach is currently used in ``ma.corrcoef`` to "
"calculate the standard deviations for each pair of variables. This has been "
"changed as it is being used to normalise the covariance, estimated using "
"``ma.cov``, which does not consider the observations for each variable in a "
"pairwise manner, rendering it unnecessary. The normalisation has been "
"replaced by the more appropriate standard deviation for each variable, which "
"significantly reduces the wall time, but will return slightly different "
"estimates of the correlation coefficients in cases where the observations "
"between a pair of variables are not aligned. However, it will return the "
"same estimates in all other cases, including returning the same correlation "
"matrix as ``corrcoef`` when using a masked array with no masked values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:334
msgid "Cast-safety fixes in ``copyto`` and ``full``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:335
msgid ""
"``copyto`` now uses NEP 50 correctly and applies this to its cast safety. "
"Python integer to NumPy integer casts and Python float to NumPy float casts "
"are now considered \"safe\" even if assignment may fail or precision may be "
"lost. This means the following examples change slightly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:342
msgid ""
"``np.copyto(int8_arr, 1000)`` previously performed an unsafe/same-kind cast"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:341
msgid ""
"of the Python integer.  It will now always raise, to achieve an unsafe cast "
"you must pass an array or NumPy scalar."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:344
msgid ""
"``np.copyto(uint8_arr, 1000, casting=\"safe\")`` will raise an OverflowError "
"rather than a TypeError due to same-kind casting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:347
msgid ""
"``np.copyto(float32_arr, 1e300, casting=\"safe\")`` will overflow to ``inf`` "
"(float32 cannot hold ``1e300``) rather raising a TypeError."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:350
msgid ""
"Further, only the dtype is used when assigning NumPy scalars (or 0-d "
"arrays), meaning that the following behaves differently:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:353
msgid "``np.copyto(float32_arr, np.float64(3.0), casting=\"safe\")`` raises."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:355
msgid ""
"``np.coptyo(int8_arr, np.int64(100), casting=\"safe\")`` raises. Previously, "
"NumPy checked whether the 100 fits the ``int8_arr``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:358
msgid ""
"This aligns ``copyto``, ``full``, and ``full_like`` with the correct NumPy 2 "
"behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.1.0-notes.rst:361
msgid "(`gh-27091 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/27091>`__)"
msgstr ""
